The paper focuses on distributed computing models for graph processing, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also deals with algorithms and lower bounds for graph problems, which is a topic in Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of large-scale graphs such as the Web graph and social networks suggests that the paper may also be relevant to Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Networked Systems (cs.NI). Finally, the study of complexity bounds for graph problems suggests that the paper may also be relevant to Computational Complexity (cs.CC).
